{
  "text": "Previous reports have demonstrated that ligamentous and/or meniscal injuries of the knee joint are uncommon in skaters. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] This study's data matched those of previous reports. The reasons underlying this phenomenon are believed to include the following: 1) in figure skating, the skater lands gliding backwards, requiring co-contraction of the quadriceps and hamstrings, which protects the ligaments and meniscus; [CITATION_5] and 2) there is a relative lack of fixation of the blade on the ice that occurs while skating. [CITATION_6] There was a difference in the right SLR angle observed between the figure and speed skaters in this study. One of the reasons for this difference is thought to be the fact that the speed skaters are only required to skate in a counterclockwise direction.",
  "correct_citation": {
